 Size and industry effects in the performance 
 of farming-based cooperatives 
 Zvi Lerman 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow and Management, Hebrew University, 
 Rehovot 76100, Israel 
 
 and Claudia Parliament 
 Department of Farming-based and Applied Money flow, University of Minnesota, 
 St. Paul, MN 55108, USA 
 (Accepted 9 July 1990) 
 
 ABSTRACT 
 Lerman, Z. and Parliament, C., 1991. Size and industry effects m the performance of 
 farming-based cooperatives. Agric. Econ., 6: 15-29. 
 The goal of this study is to decide/figure out if there are important size and industry effects 
 on (money-related) performance of farming-based cooperatives. The performance of 43 dairy, food, 
 grain, and farm supply cooperatives in the U.S. was carefully studied over the period 1970-1987 
 using (money-related) ratios came/coming from accounting data. The analysis showed/told about significant size 
 and industry effects. Large (related to a large area) cooperatives are (producing more with less waste) in using their valuable things 
 to create sales, while small (related to a large area) cooperatives have higher a money-making state. The findings 
 suggest that the focus on growth may not always produce helpful results among 
 farming-based cooperatives. Among the four businesses studied, the dairy (related to a large area) cooperatives 
 appear to be the strongest performers, while the food marketing cooperatives are seen as the lowest performance measures. Since both dairy and food cooperatives work at 
 value-added processing, this difference in performance makes it hard to reach clear 
 ends/end results about possible advantages of disadvantages or up-and-down (combination of different things together that work as one unit) relative to 
 traditional cooperative activities. Trend analysis points to/shows that the money-making ability of the 
 farming-based cooperatives in all industry and size categories (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) in response to the 
 downturn in U.S. farming after 1980. While the decline in a money-making state was at almost the same 
 rates for both large and small cooperatives, the difference/different version of (wasting very little while working or producing something) and power was in 
 opposite directions. Large cooperatives may be expected to continue improving their valuable thing 
 use without relative improvement in a money-making state, and increasing the level of their 
 (money owed)  in relation to equity. 
 
