 INTRODUCTION 
 
 Performance test of cooperatives has always been a topic of 
 a lot of interest in farming-based money flow/money-based studies, mostly because of the 
 importance of the cooperative form of organization in farming in both 
 developed and developing countries. Usually/(in the past), farming-based cooperatives have been encouraged as a vehicle for money-based development, because the cooperative form of organization, in addition to being fair, 
 enables small producers to take by force/take control of (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of size and increases their 
 marketing power. Governments jn both developed and developing countries actively (help increase/show in a good way) and help farming-based cooperatives. Reason of 
 continued public support of the cooperative form of organization needs/demands 
 test and watching of cooperative performance. 
 The goal of this study is to decide/figure out if there are significant size 
 and industry effects on performance among cooperatives. Size effects, if 
 detected, may help to decide/figure out whether cooperatives should focus on 
 growth, as has been obvious in the constant state of mergers among U.S. 
 cooperatives. Industry effects, if found, may point to/show whether the cooperative form of organization is more successful in the usual businesses of 
 input supply and raw produce marketing than in the (up and down) integrated 
 businesses that include valued-added processing. The industry results may 
 provide some (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) to resolve the conflict between cooperative planners focusing on traditional service activities and those (trying to get people to believe in and agree with something) a shift 
 toward value-added processing. 
 The next section describes the data and the way(s) of doing things. The two 
 sections that follow present the results on size and industry effects. Ends/end results and policy effects/results/suggestions are given in the last section. 
 DATA AND METHODOLOGY 
 
 (money-related) money-flow experts generally agree that (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned firms may be 
 viewed as value-(make as big as possible)rs and their performance can be measured by 
 a money-making state (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) for risk. The unemotional function of cooperatives is 
 much less clearly defined, however, especially because the cooperative 
 exists in order to provide a service to its members and the benefits of the 
 cooperative form of organization are not restricted to earning a return on 
 investment. As a result, there is a lack of accepted measures of cooperative 
 performance. 
 The present research partially overcomes this difficulty by putting into use a 
 multidimensional approach. Four measures of business performance of 
 cooperatives are examined: power, (wasting very little while working or producing something), liquidity, and a money-making state. 
 Performance is carefully studied by (money-related) ratios based on reported accounting 
 
