 The before-tax rate of return on equity is used because some cooperatives do not report 
 taxes in their income statement due to the possible hit/effect of (the money, and other help, given to a person or organization) refund policies on 
 tax (responsibility/duty). Eight cooperatives in the sample do not report (money made/good thing received) or net margins in 
 their (money-related) statements. For these cooperatives (all in the food industry), the (money made/good thing received) was 
 guessed using the way of doing things developed in Lerman and Parliament (1990a). 
 
 data, a standard way of doing things borrowed from (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned firms for (money-related) performance test of cooperatives (Babb and Lang, 1985; Chen et 
 al., 1985; Schrader et al., 1985; Parliament et al., 1990). These performance 
 measures focus on the cooperative as a business firm and do not capture 
 possible added/more benefits to members. Yet (money-related) ratios reflect the 
 effect of (related to a plan to reach a goal) decisions and should show if differences exist among 
 cooperatives in different size and industry categories. 
 Table 1 presents the definitions of the four (money-related) ratios used in this 
 research. These particular (money-related) ratios were chosen because of their 
 direct link to (related to big business) plan and goals. The relevance of these 
 (money-related) ratios for measuring the performance of cooperatives is discussed 
 by Parliament et al. (1990), who also review some different measures of 
 cooperative performance that focus on benefits to members. 
 The information file for this research consists of the audited once-a-year reports of a 
 sample of 43 U.S. (related to a large area) cooperatives for the period 1970-1987. The 
 data were collected by writing to over 200 non-(related to arriving at an agreement) cooperatives 
 listed in the Directory of Farmer Cooperatives of the USDA Farming-based 
 Cooperative Service (ACS) (Jermolowicz and Kennedy, 1989). The sample 
 includes all the people who responded that gave their once-a-year reports by the end 
 of 1989. These are mainly (related to a large area) cooperatives, almost the same  in sales volume 
 (features/ qualities/ traits) to the top 100 U.S. cooperatives regularly surveyed by ACS. 
 
