 The 43 (related to a large area) cooperatives were classified into four businesses: 12 dairy 
 cooperatives, 12 supply cooperatives, 14 food marketing and processing 
 cooperatives, and five grain and cotton marketing cooperatives. 1 The 
 cooperatives were also classified into two size categories, 'small' and 
 'large', by their total valuable things. The range of mean total valuable things of the cooperatives in the sample was from $3 million to $911 million (averaged over the 
 sample period). The distribution of mean valuable thing size for the cooperatives is 
 shown in Fig. 1. For purposes of size analysis, 29 cooperatives with mean 
 total valuable things up to $125 million were classified as 'small' and 14 cooperatives 
 with mean total valuable things of over $125 million were classified as 'large'. The 
 size classification dividing line was identified by an (related to things clustering together) group-related 
 analysis of the cooperatives by mean valuable thing size. Figure 2 presents the 
 distribution of the 43 cooperatives by industry and by size within each 
 industry. 
 
 1 There was initial doubt as to the proper classification of grain and cotton cooperatives in the sample. Because grain marketing cooperatives also sell farm inputs to their 
 members, it could be argued that they should be classified as supply cooperatives. Because 
 cotton cooperatives operate on a combining basis, it could be argued that they should be 
 classified with the combining food cooperatives. The doubt was settled by applying 
 multivariate discriminant analysis, which pointed to/showed that grain marketing cooperatives were 
 clear/separate from the supply cooperatives and furthermore could be combined with the cotton 
 cooperatives into one category. Discriminant analysis also established tha:t cotton cooperatives could not be classified with food cooperatives. It was this way decided to classify the grain 
 and cotton marketing cooperatives as a separate, although (in a true way) small, category. 
 
