 The (money-related) ratios of all the cooperatives were calculated from their 
 audited once-a-year reports for each year during the period 1970-1987. The 
 time-series data were used to trace the behavior of cooperatives in different categories over time. For each (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) year, the middle-point of each of 
 the four (money-related) ratios was calculated separately in each industry and size 
 category. In this way, a time series of 18 middle-point (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) was gotten 
 for each (money-related) ratio by industry and size categories. The middle-point was 
 chosen as the descriptive statistic because it is more strong to (things that aren't part of the main group) than 
 the mean, and examination of the data showed/told about occasional (things that aren't part of the main group). 
 The 1970-1987 time series of the middle-point (money-related) ratios were carefully studied 
 using the nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis test ("one-way analysis of variance 
 by ranks") in order to detect a big differences among industry and 
 size categories (Daniel, 1978). In application to the two size categories, the 
 Kruskal-Wallis test happens with the Wilcoxon rank-sum test. The test 
 ranks the combined middle-point (money-related) ratios in different categories and forms 
 the sums of the ranks for the combined sample. If the rank sums, or the 
 
 20 
 
 Z. LERMAN AND C. PARLIAMENT 
 
 average scores, are (good or well enough) different among the categories, the test 
 rejects the null guess that the middle-point (money-related) ratios are the same 
 across categories and establishes that, with a certain chance, the 
 industry or size categories have different middle-point (money-related) ratios. The 
 average rank scores in each category can be used to rank performance. The 
 performance ranking of the different categories over the 1970-1987 period 
 received/got in this way was (checked for truth/proved true) by Page's nonparametric test for ordered 
 other choices (Daniel, 1978). Since the Page test results confirm and reinforce the Kruskal-Wallis test results, only the last thing just mentioned are reported in full. 
 In addition to tests of the performance ranking of categories, linear 
 moving backward analysis of the middle-point time series was used to identify differences in (money-related) ratio (popular things/general ways things are going) by size and industry and to (describe the future) possible 
 future changes in the performance rankings watched/followed for the period 19701987. Trends were figured out by/decided by running ordinary least-squares (moving backwards) for each middle-point ratio on time with dummy (numbers that change/things that change) for size and 
 industry. The large cooperatives were the base for guess of moving backward 
 coefficients with size dummy (numbers that change/things that change), and the dairy category was the base 
 for moving backward coefficient guess with industry dummy (numbers that change/things that change). Two 
 groups of tests were (did/done/completed) on the guessed moving backward coefficients: (a) 
 evenness-of-slopes tests for a big difference of the guessed 
 limits/guidelines between the base category and other categories, and (b) multivariate tests for a big difference from zero of the guessed limits/guidelines going along with/matching up to different size and industry categories. 
