 (wasting very little while working or producing something)) were very different between the large and small cooperatives at the 5% level of importance. The middle-point (wasting very little while working or producing something) of valuable thing 
 use was much higher for the large cooperatives, while the 
 middle-point liquidity and a money-making state measures were much higher for the 
 small cooperatives. Only the middle-point power was not found to be very different between the two size categories. 
 To illustrate the breaking up/spreading out of the ratio values in each year, the top and 
 bottom (25% and 75%) quartiles of the (money-related) ratios were calculated for 
 each year for the large and the small cooperatives. The interquartile range 
 traces a band around the middle-point that contains 50% of the watched/followed ratio 
 values in the sample of cooperatives for each particular year (this band is 
 not necessarily matching about the middle-point). The interquartile range is a 
 nonparametric measure of breaking up/spreading out the same as standard moving away. 
 Examination of the interquartile range of the two size categories over time 
 provides a visual confirmation of the Kruskal-Wallis test results presented 
 in Table 2. 
 Figure 3 (panels a to d) places (on top of) the interquartile range of small 
 and large cooperatives for each ratio. Panel a shows that the interquartile 
 range of the leverage ratio for the large cooperatives lies almost completely 
 within the interquartile range for the small cooperatives over the period 
 1970-1987. The overlapping interquartile ranges point to/show that the middle-point 
 power is not very different for the small and the large cooperatives. 
 In panel b, the interquartile range of the (wasting very little while working or producing something) ratio for the large 
 cooperatives lies within the interquartile range for the small cooperatives 
 until about 1979, after which the top quartile value of the large cooperatives is regularly higher than the top quartile value of the small cooperatives. The graphical presentation shows/tells about that the difference between large 
 and small cooperatives became more obvious over the later period 
 1979-1987. Large cooperatives this way appear to be (producing more with less waste) than the 
 small cooperatives in using their valuable things to create sales. 
 In panel c, the top quartile of the liquidity ratio for the small cooperatives regularly lies above the top quartile for the large cooperatives, 
 while the bottom quartiles roughly overlap. This points to/shows that the small 
 cooperatives maintain a higher liquidity than the large cooperatives. 
 Panel d presents the interquartile range of the money-making ability ratio. The 
 top 25% of the rate of return on equity (RoE) for the small cooperatives lies above the upper ROE quartile for the large cooperatives in 17 out 
 of 18 years, and the bottom quartile of the small cooperatives lies above the 
 bottom quartile of the large cooperatives in 14 out of the 18 years. The ROE 
 for the small cooperatives is this way watched/followed to be higher over most of the 
 sample period than for the large cooperatives. 
 
