 (popular thing/general way things are going) analysis results for the middle-point (money-related) ratios of the large and the 
 small cooperatives are presented in Table 3. The middle-point leverage ratio 
 shows very different (popular things/general ways things are going) for the two size categories, increasing 
 over time for the large cooperatives and (lowering in number/getting worse) for the small cooperatives. If this difference continues, large cooperatives may develop in the 
 future much higher levels of (money owed)  relative to equity than the small 
 cooperatives, opposite to the pattern watched/followed between 1970 and 1987 (Fig. 
 3a). The middle-point (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the large cooperatives increases over time, 
 while that of the small cooperatives declines, which should only strengthen 
 in the future the advantage that large cooperatives had between 1970 and 
 1987 in using their valuable things to create sales (Fig. 3b). Both a money-making state 
 and liquidity show/tell about a (lowering in number/getting worse) (popular thing/general way things are going), but the rate of decline is not 
 very different for the large and the small cooperatives, which 
 hints that the advantage in a money-making state and liquidity watched/followed for the 
 small cooperatives between 1970 and 1987 may be maintained in the 
 future. 
 So, while the large cooperatives are watched/followed to be (producing more with less waste) in 
 using their valuable things to create sales, the small cooperatives have higher 
 a money-making state and liquidity. The results suggest that large cooperatives may 
 enjoy scale (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) in terms of (wasting very little while working or producing something), but the benefits of size do not 
 necessarily translate into higher a money-making state. The higher rate of return on 
 equity for the small cooperatives is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the "small-firm effect" 
 watched/followed for (person or business who gives money to help start a business) owned corporations, which shows that (people or businesss who give money to help start businesses) in 
 small firms usually earn higher rates of return on investment [see Levy and 
 Lerman (1985) and references (in there/within that)]. With respect to liquidity, it could 
 be guessed that small firms, with a (compared to other things) small valuable thing base, prefer 
 to maintain a higher liquidity buffer than large, valuable thing-rich firms. With 
 respect to take advantage of, it could (in almost the same way) be argued that small cooperatives 
 would have a lower power than the large, more secure cooperatives. 
