 INDUSTRY EFFECTS 
 
 Clear industry effects were found for all middle-point (money-related) ratios. The 
 Kruskal-Wallis test results (Table 4) show that for leverage, (wasting very little while working or producing something), and 
 liquidity the industry effects were significant at 1%. The (related to studying numbers) test 
 results are visually proven true by the time series graphs in Fig. 4 (panels a 
 to d). The graphs in Fig. 4 plot only the middle-point ratios by industry over the 
 period 1970-1987, as it was not doable to place (on top of) the interquartile ranges for the four businesses. 
 The leverage ratio (panel a) was found to be the highest for the food 
 marketing cooperatives and the lowest for the supply cooperatives, with the 
 dairy and grain cooperatives lying in the middle. 
 The four businesses are also clearly (made different) by (wasting very little while working or producing something) (panel b). 
 Dairies regularly have thee highest (wasting very little while working or producing something), followed by grain and 
 supply cooperatives in this order, with the food marketing cooperatives 
 regularly at the bottom of the ranking. 
 Liquidity is the highest for dairy and supply cooperatives, which both 
 have (compared to other things) high quick ratios near the level of 1.0 (panel c), while food 
 and grain cooperatives have (compared to other things) low quick ratios around 0.5. The 
 Kruskal-Wallis test points to/shows that only the differences between the food 
 and grain cooperatives are not significant. 
 The differences in a money-making state between dairy, food, and grain cooperatives are not (meaningful numbers). Yet the middle-point ROE of the cooperatives in these three businesses combined is much higher than that of 
 
