 The (popular things/general ways things are going) of the middle-point (money-related) ratios by industry are presented in 
 Table 5. The middle-point (money owed)  to equity ratios of the cooperatives in the four 
 businesses show a coming together (popular thing/general way things are going), mainly as a result of the declining 
 power of the dairy and food cooperatives and the increasing power of 
 the supply cooperatives (compare Fig. 4a). It might be guessed that the 
 highly (including a lot of debt) food and dairy cooperatives got good things from wearing away of 
 their fixed-rate (money owed)  in the inflationary period 1973-1980: their equity 
 part may have increased through unrealized (when things become more valuable), driving 
 the leverage ratio down over time. The middle-point sales to valuable things ratio of the 
 dairy, food, and supply cooperatives does not show a significant (popular thing/general way things are going) over 
 time, and the relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) ranking of these businesses will probably be 
 maintained in the future (Fig. 4b). The grain cooperatives show a big improvement of their sales to valuable things ratio, and as a result may 
 challenge in the future the top ranking dairy cooperatives. The rate of 
 return on equity (RoE) shows/tells about a significant (lowering in number/getting worse) (popular thing/general way things are going) for cooperatives 
 in three of the four businesses; only the guessed coefficient of the food 
 cooperatives, while negative, is not very different from zero. The 
 guessed decline in middle-point ROE may be due to the general downturn in 
 the U.S. farming-based part/area during the 1980s, as separate analysis using only 
 the 1970-1979 data did not show/tell about significant downward (popular things/general ways things are going) in a money-making state during the pre-1980 ten years for three out of the four businesses 
 (except the grain cooperatives). 
