 CONCLUSION 
 
 One of the (constant/not going away) (popular things/general ways things are going) among cooperatives is growth through 
 mergers and purchases. The findings of this study point to/show that although 
 larger cooperatives improve (wasting very little while working or producing something) through (making a lot of an item so each item costs less), the 
 higher (wasting very little while working or producing something) of valuable thing use does not translate into higher a money-making state. This hints that the benefits of mergers may be put way too much focus on, 
 which is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with recent findings pointing to/showing that the money-making ability of 
 cooperatives does not very much improve after a merger (Parliament and 
 Taitt, 1989). 
 The industry effects showed in this study do not provide definite 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) to support either side of the (related to a plan to reach a goal) conflict between the 
 fighters (for something) of traditional service activities and the fighters (for something) of (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) through value-added processing. The dairy cooperatives, which engage 
 in value-added processing, are the highest ranking performers among the 
 four businesses by leverage, (wasting very little while working or producing something), liquidity, and a money-making state ratios. The 
 food cooperatives, on the other hand, are at the bottom of the ranking, 
 although they also work at long/big value-added processing. 
 The grain and supply cooperatives, which have generally limited their 
 activities to the usual areas of raw produce marketing and input 
 buying, show a higher performance ranking than the food cooperatives 
 working at value-added processing. It could be argued that the (compared to other things) 
 strong performance of the dairy cooperatives in the U.S. is related to 
 government (promised that something will definitely happen or that something will definitely work as described) prices for the take from used in dairy products. If this is 
 
 28 
 
 Z. LERMAN AND C. PARLIAMENT 
 
 in fact so, the inferior performance of the food processing cooperatives 
 may be understood/explained as agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with the view that, without 
 clearly stated/particular support programs for value-added processing, cooperatives should 
 think about/believe restricting their scope to traditional activities. 
 In a recent comparison of cooperatives and (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned firms (Lerman and Parliament, 1990b), the food cooperatives were found to have a 
 weaker performance than the (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned firms in the same industry by 
 three of the six performance measures thought about/believed while the dairy cooperatives (did/done/completed) not worse than the (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned dairies by all measures. 
 These findings point to/show that the (compared to other things) weak performance of the food 
 cooperatives watched/followed in the present study cannot be completely attributed to 
 industry-clearly stated/particular factors. There are indications that, of the two value-added 
 processing businesses, the dairy cooperatives have a higher proportion of 
 pass-through sales than the food-processing cooperatives: the proportion of 
 fluid milk sales in dairies is higher than the proportion of raw produce 
 sales in food-processing cooperatives. These factors also could be understood/explained as supporting the view that (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) into value-added processing 
 has not been a total success for cooperatives. 
 An international comparison is given by a recent study of two 
 (related to a large area) farming-based cooperatives in Israel (Yacobi, 1989), where the cooperative working at value-added food processing had much higher 
 power, lower a money-making state, and lower (wasting very little while working or producing something) than the cooperative that 
 limited its activities to raw produce marketing. The Israeli comparison, however limited, appears to support those who believe that manufacturing of 
 value-added person products may not be a especially good 
 activity for cooperatives, (even though there is the existence of) the attraction of forward (combination of different things together that work as one unit). Cooperatives may find it hard to get the necessary useful things/valuable supplies for successful 
 penetration of the personal food markets. 
 Support programs, product mix, and market (features/ qualities/ traits) are (in the end) responsible for success or failure of value-added processing. Further 
 research is needed in order to identify and separate the government 
 support part in the performance of U.S. dairy cooperatives and to 
 carefully study the cooperatives in the two valued-added processing businesses on 
 the basis of the clearly stated/particular mix of pass-through sales and value-added products. More described/explained comparisons between cooperatives and (person or business who gives money to help start a business)-owned 
 firms in corresponding businesses are needed in order to separate between 
 industry-specific and cooperative-clearly stated/particular factors. This added/more research 
 may produce more definite results (related to/looking at/thinking about) the debate between supporters of traditional cooperatives and fights (for something) of up-and-down (combination of different things together that work as one unit). At 
 this stage, the striking difference in performance between the two valueadded processing businesses in our sample makes it hard to generalize 
 about the relative good qualities of value-added processing for cooperatives. 
 
